{
  "texts": [
    "Despite these advances in imaging modalities, the analysis of fossil image datasets is a predominantly manual process, with the inspection, segmentation (i.e., the process of partitioning images into meaningful regions, such as isolating the fossil from the surrounding matrix or distinguishing different anatomical structures), and categorization of imaged specimens into taxonomic ranks requiring significant manual intervention by an expert paleontologist (Rodgers and Tilley 2004).",
    "This process is time-consuming and prone to biases (Forey et al. 2004; Eberth et al. 2007; Lloyd et al. 2012), with each task requiring attention to detail and significant expertise.",
    "Segmentation and subsequent classification-both crucial for inferring phylogeny, life mode and ecological niche-are particularly challenging, often requiring expert intervention (Rohlf and Marcus 1993; Bookstein 1997; Parham et al. 2012; Adams and Otárola-Castillo 2013).",
    "Artificial intelligence (AI) encompasses the development of systems capable of performing tasks that typically require human cognitive functions, such as problem-solving and decision-making (McCarthy and Hayes 1981).",
    "Machine learning (ML), a subset of AI, focuses on creating algorithms that enable systems to learn patterns from data and improve performance on tasks without explicit programming (Mitchell 1997)."
  ]
}